Introducing computational thinking to K-12 students generally relies on the availability of computer science (CS) classes and varies by school type and location. This study focuses on how location and the type(s) of school(s) students attend may impact their access to CS education and their resulting AI literacy. 2024-2025 AI literacy survey and focus group interview responses provided by students and CS curricula of schools are analyzed. ANOVA and post-hoc Tukey tests were performed to compare AI literacy levels of students attending different types of schools. ANOVA tests revealed that school type and county were significant at the p < 0.1 cutoff for the 2025 sample. Focus group findings revealed that students may not be receiving CS education as stated by their schools.